Problem 1.1

(a)

We will investigate if there is a linear trend in the measurements of temperatures in Ann Arbor, Michigan, by fitting a linear model for the temperature as a response with time (in years) as the explanatory variable.

lmod <- lm(temp ~ year, data=aatemp)
summary(lmod)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = temp ~ year, data = aatemp)
## 
## Residuals:
##     Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max 
## -3.9843 -0.9113 -0.0820  0.9946  3.5343

## Coefficients:
##              Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)

## Multiple R-squared:  0.08536,    Adjusted R-squared:  0.07727 
## F-statistic: 10.55 on 1 and 113 DF,  p-value: 0.001533

Here, we see that the parameter for year is significant in describing the response as a slight, positive trend. However, the fit to the data is very poor, with an adjusted \(R^2_a\) only around 0.07.

We can verify this graphically as,

plot(temp ~ year, data=aatemp, xlab="Year", ylab="Temperature Farenheit", main="Annual mean temperature over Ann Arbor")
abline(coef(lmod))

While there appears to be an increasing trend for the data overall, it doesn’t seem to be linear necessarily.

Performing diagnostics plots, likewise,

plot(lmod)

there appears to be nonlinear structure in the residuals.

(b)

We will fit an autoregressive model to determine if there is correlation between successive years in the measurement of temperature. Particularly, we will use the “embed” function to create a lag-1 dataframe for the model,

lag_df <- embed(aatemp$temp, dimension=2)
colnames(lag_df) <- c("y", "lag_1")
lag_df <- data.frame(lag_df)
head(lag_df)

With respect to this lag-1 dataframe, we now model,

auto_lm <- lm(y ~ lag_1, data=lag_df)
summary(auto_lm)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = y ~ lag_1, data = lag_df)
## 
## Residuals:
##     Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max 
## -3.9553 -0.9393 -0.0289  0.9702  4.3910 
## 
## Coefficients:
##             Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept) 35.57600    4.34886   8.181 4.91e-13 ***
## lag_1        0.25460    0.09105   2.796  0.00609 ** 
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 1.483 on 112 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.06526,    Adjusted R-squared:  0.05691 
## F-statistic: 7.819 on 1 and 112 DF,  p-value: 0.006086

and we find that there is a linear relationship between the temperature measurements in successive years with \(5\%\) significance.

If we considered what the model for the trend would look like over time as a simple, lag-1 autoregressive model, this would say that approximately:

\[\begin{align} y_k = 35.6 + .25 y_{k-1} + \epsilon_k \end{align}\]

Therefore, if \(\overline{y}_k \triangleq \mathbb{E}\left[y_k \right]\), we can derive a recusion for the mean temperature \(\overline{y}_k\) as

\[\begin{align} \overline{y}_k = \frac{\overline{y}_0}{4^{k}} + \sum_{i=1}^k \frac{35.6}{4^{k-i}} \end{align}\]

This actually has a limiting value as

\[\begin{align} \lim_{k\rightarrow \infty} \frac{\overline{y}_0}{4^{k}} =0 \end{align}\]

for any finite initial mean temperature. Secondly, the sum is a convergent geometric series with limit,

\[\begin{align} \lim_{k\rightarrow \infty} \sum_{i=1}^k \frac{35.6}{4^{k-i}} &= \lim_{k\rightarrow \infty} 35.6\left(\frac{1 - .25^k}{1-.25}\right)\\ &= 35.6 \left(\frac{1}{1 - .25}\right)\\ & \approx 47.46667 \end{align}\]

We can define a quick function to give the mean response according to the geometric recursion,

tmp_trend <- function(k,y_0) return (y_0/(4^(k)) + 35.6*( (1-.25^k) / (.75) ))

from which we can plot the auto-regressive form of the trend over the data (using the mean temp before 1900 as a naive initial condition):

auto_trend <- tmp_trend(aatemp$year - 1853, mean(aatemp$temp[aatemp$year < 1900])) 
plot(temp ~ year, data=aatemp, xlab="Year", ylab="Temperature Farenheit", main="Annual mean temperature over Ann Arbor")
points(aatemp$year,auto_trend, pch=4)

While there clearly seems to be correlation between the temperatures in successive years, the auto-regressive model doesn’t seem appropriate either in describing the overall trend. It appears again that there is some nonlinear phenomenon.

Problem 1.2

We will fit a model with O3 as the response, and temp, humidity and ibh as predictors. We have,

lmod <- lm(O3 ~ temp + humidity + ibh, data=ozone)
summary(lmod)

## 
## Residual standard error: 4.524 on 326 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.684,  Adjusted R-squared:  0.6811 
## F-statistic: 235.2 on 3 and 326 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16
plot(lmod)

We notice that there is strong indications of non-constant variance of the error and nonlinear structure in the residuals. We will perform a Box-Cox transformation on the response “O3” to see if this eliminates the issues.

boxcox(lmod, plotit=T, lambda=seq(0,1,by=0.1))

With respect to the Box-Cox \(95\%\) condidence interval, we see that the transformation by \(y\mapsto y^{1/3}\) or \(y\mapstoy^{1/3}\) are both plausible values for a transformation, and we securely rule out the null mapping.

We compare thus the transformation by the quartic and cubic roots:

lmod <- lm(O3^(1/4) ~ temp + humidity + ibh, data=ozone)
summary(lmod)

As both transformations appear to deal with the nonlinearity in the residuals and the non-constant variance, both seem appropriate. We might favor the quartic root due to the lower standard error, but the difference overall is negligible.

Here, if there was a physically consistent reason to consider a model without intercept, where the lpsa should be zero when the explanatory variables are zero, we could consider removing this as well.

(b)

Here we will use the “regsubsets” of the “MASS” library to perform an exhaustive search over the models. In particular, we get

sum_prost <- summary(regsubsets(lpsa ~ ., data=prostate))
sum_prost

from which we can see the explanatory variables used within the “best” model of each number of predictors.

To compute the AIC, this unfortunately is manual (unlike the BIC) that can be printed from the summary like so:

sum_prost$bic
## [1] -66.05415 -71.80379 -77.21486 -75.31573 -72.76362 -69.60319 -66.47110
## [8] -61.98694

To get the AIC values, we compute

AIC <- 97*log(sum_prost$rss/97) + (2:9)*2

where:

  1. 97 corresponds to the total number of observations;
  2. the vector of 2 - 9 corresponds to the number of parameters (explanatory variables plus 1 intercept term);
  3. the RSS is is numerator of the fraction in the log function above.

Printing the vector of the values for the AIC, we find

AIC
## [1] -44.36608 -52.69043 -60.67621 -61.35179 -61.37439 -60.78867 -60.23130
## [8] -58.32184

the AIC is minimized for the model with 5 explanatory variables, i.e., lcavol, lweight, age, lbph and svi.

(c)

We can also make a selection based on the adjusted \(R^2_a\) as follows:

sum_prost$adjr2
## [1] 0.5345838 0.5771246 0.6143899 0.6208036 0.6245476 0.6258707 0.6272521
## [8] 0.6233681

Here we find that the adjusted \(R^2_a\) attains a maximum value for the model including all explanatory variables except for gleason.

(d)

Finally, we study the fit using Mallow’s Cp statistic. Here, numbers around the line \(C_p =\) “number of parameters” are favored, but we always favor smaller models and ones with \(C_p\) value under the line. Here the best choice is with five explanatory variables (6 parameters).

plot(c(2:9),sum_prost$cp, xlab = "Number of parameters", ylab="Mallows Cp")
abline(0,1)
